Younger. This has been held to be no part.of a man's name, but an addition by use, and a convenient distinction be- —

tween a father and son of the same name. Cobb v. Lucas, 15 Pick. (Mass.) 9; People v. Collins, 7 Johns. (N. Y.) 552; Padgett v. Lawrence, 10 Paige (N. Y.) 177, 40 Am. Dec 232; Prentiss v. Blake, 34 Vt. 460. Junior right. A custom prevalent in some parts of Engiand (also at some places on the continent) by which an estate descended to the youngest son in preference to his older brothers;

the same as "Borough-Knglish.". As to junior "Barrister," 'Counsel," "Creditor," "Execution," "Judgment," and "Writ," see those titles.
